            <fileData><![CDATA[<#-- title: Potable Water -->
<main class="pt-28 pb-16">
    <section class="max-w-container mx-auto px-4 md:px-12 py-8">
        <h1 class="font-display text-4xl font-bold text-on-surface mb-6">Potable Water Liners</h1>
        <div class="max-w-3xl space-y-5 text-on-surface-variant leading-relaxed">
            <p>
                Potable water is water that must be safe for human consumption. Check local
                regulations for the liner materials approved for use in your area.
            </p>
            <p>
                Most areas require that liners for potable water are certified by the National
                Sanitation Foundation (NSF) to meet the NSF/ANSI 61 standard. NSF certified liners
                are inspected to ensure that all ingredients, including the polymer and additives
                such as UV stabilizers, heat stabilizers and antioxidants, are safe for contact with
                drinking water.
            </p>
            <p>
                Common liner materials for potable water are NSF certified 36 and 45 mil
                Polypropylene.
            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="mt-8">
            <a href="/content/contact" class="bg-primary hover:bg-primary/90 text-on-primary font-label text-sm font-medium px-6 py-3 rounded-lg l-glow transition-all inline-flex items-center gap-2">
                Ask about NSF certified liners
            </a>
        </div>
    </section>
</main>]]></fileData>
